The following passage of Cyril also shows him to have besu of the same opinion: “As when any one pours melted wax upon other wax, the whole will be mingled together into one mass, so it is necessary to any persou's reception of the body and blood of Christ, for him to be united with Christ, so that Christ may be found in him, and he in Christ.'' These words,l think, sufficiently prove, that those who eat the body of Christ merely in a sacramental way are deprived of the true and real participatiou of it, as the body itself cannot be separated from its efficacious power 3 and yet that this is no impeachment of the truth of the promises of God, who still continues to send us rain from heaven, though rocks and stenes imbibe none of the moisture.
